<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-721-356  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 721 356.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  August 10 1990 v139 pC3(N) pD3(L) 9 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Baby Bells' $2.4 billion deal gains. (Bell Atlantic Corp. andAmeritech to acquire Telecom Corporation of New Zealand)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Edmund L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Judge Harold H. Greene rules to allow regional Bell companies BellAtlantic Corp and Ameritech to retain control of internationalservices provided by the Telecom Corporation of New Zealand.andO;Greene's ruling removes a legal uncertainty in a proposed $2.4million acquisition of Telecom Corporation by the Bell companies.andO;Until now, the Bell companies had been prohibited from providinglong-distance services under Judge Greene's 1984 consent decree,which dismantled the Bell System.andP;  Greene's decision was opposedby American long-distance companies MCI Communications Corp and USSprint.andP;  Those companies had argued that a ruling that favored theBell companies would stifle competition in service between NewZealand and the US.andP;  The Bells will not provide direct servicebetween New Zealand and the US.andP;  They will also limit theirownership of international cable and satellite properties to 10percent.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (acquisitions and mergers)American Information Technologies Corp. (acquisitions and mergers)Telecom Corporation of New Zealand Ltd. (acquisitions andmergers).andO;Ticker:    BEL; AIT.andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesNew ZealandTelephone companiesAcquisition.andO;Person:    Greene, Harold (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>